I use an 8bitdo controller and it doesn't recognize the triggers in digital or analog mode, so I can't use special abilities without touching the screen. It's a huge pain in the butt to do that, so I don't use the special abilities at all. I don't know why there isn't an option to rebind the key to any of the other buttons that are totally recognized. I'd like to use the special abilities.

Great twin stick shooter with roguelike elements, runs well, and no BS in-app purchases, worth the price. Set a kind of techno-punk dystopian futurue with a good soundtrack, you play "runs" progressing up a ladder style of levels towards a final boss at the top, but If you die, you start over with a new character. There are hard checkpoints so as to not start at the very beginning each time, and upgrades that apply to all "runs" can be purchased with credits found in game.

The game is just great. I haven't checked if it came before JYDGE or after, but I guess it's latter. Controls are fine, there's nothing wrong with them. Gameplay if fun, although I got bored after killing fifth Overseer (got all non-secret unlockables), because everything is unlocked and maxed out and it just has more enemies. Cyber psycho has more benefits as class then any other (because you get all that extra energy, HP and speed form nanotech simbiotes), other classes quirks do not seem to be compelling enough after a while. JYDGE was much better in terms of music, soundtrack here is much more repetitive and limited. I like replayability, although it does seem to just get general outline of the levels from some limited pool, so it's sequence, loot and enemies change, but maps and bosses are getting more and more familiar with every playthrough (hell, on 3 Overseer and after only final boss beared some challenge, and probably that obnoxious spider robot Trinity (because grenade and rocket spamming in limited space, duh)). Overall I got even more fun for what I paid, would love to play again.

A well crafted shooter, with a "blade runner" atmosphere. The weapons are fun and blowing up entire levels is great. I really enjoyed the 1st run. 2nd was ok. And now I will delete. About 8hrs of fun for me. Cons: the AI is not challenging, no real individual or group tactics, you can kill a guy with an gun, or break down a wall and nobody else moves; the replay value is ok maybe twice for most people, after that it is just repeat, with harder enemies, not smarter; finally the different playable characters are all pretty much the same, even if they have minor differences in states, basically just lip service to unique gameplay styles.

Few hours in Im starting to hate the controls. Getting constantly stuck on 
objects, walk next to a wall slows the char down without any obvious 
reason, avoiding enemy fire is becoming a hassle instead of a 
challenge/skill. I liked the huge amount of finetuning although I wish it 
was more meaningful instad of a brainless max it all scheme. I like the 
large amount of weapons, although I wish they were more distinctly 
different besides lasergun a, plasmagun a, blandgun a and lasergun b, 
plasmagun b, blandgun b etc. Sniper has a better approach through piercing 
shots. I like the large amount of nanotech upgrade, but again there is 
sensible choices and stupid ones. Yes I want double ammo, no I dont want my 
char to autodrop extragrenades that hit me more than anything. Yes I want 
50% more health, no I dont want double melee damage with clumsy controls. 
Again I must ask: "Where is a clever, playstyle regarding choice?" Overall 
its better than I expected a topdown shooter to be. Getting it on a sale 
was fine, full price Id find hard to digest. The potential to make it truly 
stand out has been closely missed. Despite my critical evaluation I 
encourage the devs to put in that extra mile. I find there arent many truly 
amazing games available for phones. Imagine you re the ones to create 
"that" title.

Nevertheless, it seems that the exterior backgrounds were a little bit abandoned during development of the game! Good graphics, sound, controls and gameplay... I like it! content: Watch your back, human. In this Blade Runner-esque world, millions of humans have began living in arcologies entrusting their lives to the mercy of an AI, the Overseer. Then it goes rogue.  This game is such a stellar twin stick shooter, I don't know where to begin discussing it. Oozing with style from the start, it even has a narrative elegantly presented to you from the levels themselves without interrupting the gameplay.  Neon Chrome is an extremely energetic 'roguelite' with randomized levels and threats as you smash, shoot, detonate the whole arcology on the way to the Overseer. What seems like a simple move-and-shoot game at first evolves into a game of playing an impromptu-developed character with upgrades that change the way you play.  Do you want to become a stealthy, backstabbing assassin? Sure! Do you want to hack your way into secure vaults and unlock special equipment? Yes! How about a guy who shoots explosives, make enemies drop and detonate explosives, and cause a chain reaction that nearly destroys everything in your screen? Totally! (and that's how I one-seated Overseer 2.0!)  I realize the game has been out on Steam for a while but I hope there's more on the way!
Well worth $10. Game is matured, looks great, plays smoothly.

Overall this is a solid game with the potential for many hours of gameplay. I do have two gripes, however: playing on the Nvidia Shield K1 tablet, my device gets very hot while playing, even with graphics on the medium setting. That really shouldn't be happening on this device. Second, while I'm hugely grateful for controller support, pressing the reload button (X) for some odd reason brings up my on screen keyboard. That means in order to reload, I have to hit X, then quickly hit B to get rid of the keyboard. The instructions seem to imply B should also reload, but it (alone or in combination with the X button - instructions were unclear so I tried both) brings up and backs out of the pause screen menu - essentially it seems to act as a "back" button might. Which would be fine if X reloaded without bringing up the keyboard, but as it is, it's rather frustrating. Fix these issues and you'll have a five star game. As it is, it's more like 3.5 - 4 stars.

replyContent: You are able to continue from 1st boss after killing it. Enter the 2nd elevator instead of the 1st. The game is a "roguelite", so there are no constant checkpoints in every level. You'll keep the loot after you die though. You must complete the 4-5 lvls and kill the boss to unlock the next elevator. If this is not working for you, let us know.
